	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=2076><span id=Sage>Pusbag</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>4173 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.66]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Akashik, <br>What you say is very true in that different servers have different prices.&nbsp;&nbsp;I don't know why that is the case other than new servers having fewer of any given item thus driving the price up, but for the older servers prices become fixed at some point when there seems to be a concensus that an items' base price has been reached regardless of how many of these particular items are found or made.  And it isn't uniform across the servers either.  Servers have wildly varying prices for things, but I bet the classes are equally represented across all the servers.<br> <br>Take the serp bracer for instance:  for months these were THE item to have as a monk, and were generally sold  for around 150-200 pp on Druzzil Ro until the point that it was shown AGI above 75 gained a monk nothing except a small AC increase.  Then the price dropped to as low as 15 pp!  Mind you, the supply was always there-- it wasn't like people were suddenly flocking to Guk to beat up the mob for their serp bracer-- it's just that folks artificially inflated the price for months because of it's "must have" status. <br> <br>The weird thing is the server population on most of the older servers remain stable, so it is not that there is a high turnover of characters starting over with nothing on their persons.  You would think prices would mimic the real world by starting high when scarcity is prevalent, then drop as demand is met and supply reaches a saturation point in the market.  But it doesn't! Prices remain set regardless of how many there are available.<br><br>The only explanation for this that I can come up with is that this is a make-believe world and so the laws of supply and demand are suspended leaving issues of money, wealth, and capitalism to be concepts not applicable in Norrath.  After all, you can rusty sword after rusty sword to the merchants and he always quotes the same price.  But still, you would think prices would fluctuate as more and more of an item come on the market.<br><br>Any ideas?!?<br><br>--Pusbag Infection, who is still scratching his head in puzzlement.<br><br>/em Pusbag tries to explain to a seller of a fighting baton why 1K is unreasonable since there are fifteen people selling them for EXACTLY the same price, but gets cussed out for wasting the seller's time.</p>&nbsp;<br>I wish I was my dog. He gets to stick his nose in places I can only dream of.<br></td></td></tr>
